english:
  title: Preface to a Poem Celebrating Kang's Appointment as Royal Secretary
  author: Lee Sung-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Kang of Gyunjung has long been my companion—we served together in the Remonstrance Office and studied together at the National Academy. In deliberating affairs, he was earnest and incisive; in expounding the classics, meticulous and thorough. I deferred to him, as did all our colleagues, who felt none could match him. Park Ja-heo of Milyang, a man of integrity and principle, once told me: "Though Kang is young in years, his character bears the weight of age. Among our peers, who shall rise to prominence but he?" I took this to heart.

    When Kang was selected to enter the Ministry of Personnel as Assistant Examiner, he treated all with fairness and handled affairs with swift competence, earning ever greater praise. Soon after, he was promoted to Vice Royal Secretary. His mentor, Han of Yuhang, composed a poem in celebration. Kang gave me this poem, saying: "Our mentor once served as Royal Secretary under King Gongmin, as you know. Thus the poem speaks of inheriting the master's mantle. I wish to seek responses from the literary officials to honor our mentor's legacy. Will you not write a preface to these verses?"

    I considered: Kang's appointment to Royal Secretary reflects public consensus. Where public consensus dwells, the whole nation celebrates—how much more his mentor, how much more a friend of so many years' companionship! I write this preface at his request.

    The title "Royal Secretary" originates in the Book of Shang—it is the office of prime minister, which the High Lord granted to Fu Yue. The ancient text reads: "Morning and evening, offer your counsel. Open your heart to illumine mine." Is not this office of immense weight? Though the State's office of Royal Secretary appears subordinate to that of Prime Minister, surely the intent in creating this post deems its import weightier still. For while a Prime Minister approaches the throne at appointed times, such limitations mean the intimacy between ruler and subject cannot match the proximity of one who stands always at hand. Open remonstrance is harder than silent prevention. But the Royal Secretary, morning and evening at the sovereign's side, stands ever within arm's reach of the imperial countenance. Through such closeness, affection deepens. When affection flows freely, words are readily heard and counsel readily enacted. When words are heard and counsel enacted, we may truly speak of offering wisdom and illumining the mind. The gradual transformation and deep saturation by which the Royal Secretary cultivates the sovereign's virtue in leisure and private moments differs vastly from those whose access is circumscribed by time.

    Alas, what burden falls upon one who holds this office! I have witnessed how King Gongmin held this selection in high regard—the world looked upon those chosen as if they had ascended to the heavens themselves. Han of Yuhang was among these few. Now our present Sovereign, luminous in wisdom and versed in antiquity, advances capable talents, fearing only that merit go unrecognized. The arts of government flourish abundantly. In this propitious hour, Kang receives the glorious mandate, attending to the imperial ear at the incense table—like a feather riding a gentle wind. The people have every reason to rejoice.

    Yet consider: that Kang should occupy this office is altogether fitting, with abundance to spare. What cause for congratulation could this be? Hereafter, when he takes his seat in the halls of state, harmonizing counsel and opening hearts to illuminate the imperial mind, permitting no ancient worthy to monopolize such glory—then shall Park Ja-heo's words prove prophetic, and this humble preface be vindicated.
  footnotes:
    - 'Royal Secretary (代言): An office of intimate counsel to the throne, originating from the ancient Chinese concept where the High Lord of Shang commanded Fu Yue to offer daily wisdom.'
    - The "inherited mantle" (衣鉢) refers to the succession of a mentor's authority and wisdom, a Buddhist-influenced metaphor.
    - 'King Gongmin: The monarch under whom Han of Yuhang previously served as Royal Secretary, suggesting an established lineage of excellence in the office.'
